[2]
Date: 31 Aug 2009
Source: MPBN.net [edited]
<http://www.mpbn.net/News/MaineNews/tabid/181/ctl/ViewItem/mid/3475/ItemId/8832/Default.aspx>


State Health Officials Say Triple E Spreading Across State
----------------------------------------------------------
For years it was perceived largely as a southern New England virus
contracted by horses that were bitten by infected mosquitos. But now
Eastern Equine Encephalitis, better known as Triple E, has leapt
across the New Hampshire border area where it was identified a few
years ago and is moving into the northern regions of Maine.

Dr. Don Hoenig, the state's veterinarian, says he's never seen an
outbreak like this. "Right now we have 4 other horses pending, 3
horses that have died, one in York County, one in Cumberland County
and another one in [the town of] Unity, and a sick horse in Unity
right now that we're waiting to hear on today," Honig said today at an
Augusta news conference.

For horse owners, the truly frightening reality of this virus is that
there is no effective treatment for the illness, which can peak within
24 hours of the animal's 1st symptoms. Hoenig says vaccinations are
the only means of preventing the spread of the virus and he's urging
all horse owners to protect their animals.

"Once they get it, they either die or they're euthanized -- it
approaches 100 percent. There's really no treatment other than
supportive treatment. And I'm astonished at how quickly this disease
progresses from a horse being normal to being comatose. I went and
looked at a horse on Friday afternoon [28 Aug 2009] that we euthanized
out in Unity, and that horse was normal on Thursday morning and by 3
o'clock on Friday afternoon it was pretty much flat out and comatose,"
he says.

"The concern we have, particularly now that schools are reconvening is
that people are aware that they should take precautions over the next
few weeks to avoid getting bitten by mosquitoes," says Dr. Dora Anne
Mills, Director of the Maine Center for Disease Control.

Mills says there's only been one recorded case of a human death from
Triple E in Maine and that occurred last year in [the town of] Naples.
But Mills says the 73-year-old man had been traveling in other states,
making it difficult to determine whether he actually contracted the
virus here.

Because the virus has been discovered in Waldo County and Penobscot
County, Mills says Mainers need to be on their guard. "Although the
risk from any one mosquito bite giving you Triple E is very low, it is
not an infection you want to take a risk at getting," she warns. "It's
an infection where about a 3rd of those people with symptoms die; it's
a disease where about half the people who survive it have long-term
neurological permanent damage; and there's no vaccine for people, and
there's no effective treatment for people."

Mills says the virus poses a particular threat to those over 50 or
under 15 years of age. She urged Mainers to wear clothing that covers
their extremeties when spending time outside, and using insect
repellants that contain DEET.

[Byline: A.J. Higgins]

