[3]
Date: 31 Aug 2009
Source: MPBN.net [edited]
<http://www.mpbn.net/news/MaineHeadlineNews/tabid/968/ct/Viewtem/mid/3479/ItemID/8823/Default.aspx>


Another Horse in Maine Dies of Triple-E
---------------------------------------
The most recent equine victim was from Penobscot County, while the
other 2 infected horses lived in Waldo County.

A 3rd horse in Maine has died from the virus known as triple-E. Maine
Center for Disease Control Director Dr. Dora Mills says the horse
lived in Stetson, located in Penobscot County.

In addition to the 3 known cases, State Health Director Dr. Dora Mills
says there are 4 other suspected cases of EEE in Maine horses. 3 of
those animals have died and one is critically ill. Those horses are
located in York, Cumberland and Waldo counties.

In addition, 2 other horses, both in Waldo County, were euthanized
earlier this month [August 2009] after contracting the virus. The
disease is fatal in horses, and there is no cure.

While people can't contract the virus directly from horses, they can
get sickened by a bite from an infected mosquito. Many people who
become infected show no symptoms, Mills says, but among those who do,
the illness is fatal in about one-third of cases, and about half of
symptomatic victims who survive are left with mild to severe permanent
neurological damage.

Mills says people should protect themselves from mosquito bites by
using an effective insect repellent such as DEET, covering up with
long-sleeve shirts, pants and socks when outdoors and placing mosquito
netting over infant carriers.

She says horses can be vaccinated against the disease. None of the 3
horses that have died had been vaccinated, she says.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Correspondent Susan Baekeland

[The eastern seaboard of the US has had an abundance of rain this
year. This has left puddles in unusual places that are perfect
breeding locations for mosquitoes.

It is sad, indeed, that the investment in a horse is lost because of
this disease, when there are vaccines to prevent the disease. The
immunity incurred from the vaccine is short-lived and it is advisable
to vaccinate 2 or 3 times a year.

Yes, while people may acquire the disease from the mosquito, there are
measures to protect yourself. Some of those measures were found in the
article above. It may also be wise to avoid being outside without
repellent in the dawn and the dusk of the evening. - Mod.TG]

